          "body": "The chapter's second half opens with a single verse (5:9) that is one of the Bible's most compressed portraits of a soul destroyed by honor-hunger. Haman leaves the banquet 'glad and pleased of heart' — the same heart-vocabulary used of Israel's joy before the Lord (1 Kings 8:66; Psalm 104:15). But his joy is entirely contingent on external recognition. The sight of Mordecai unmoved at the gate is enough to collapse it entirely: 'Haman was filled with anger against Mordecai' (5:9). He controls himself publicly (5:10), goes home, and performs what Swindoll calls the 'self-inventory of a man addicted to status': riches, sons, royal promotion, the queen's private invitation — four items catalogued with increasing specificity (5:11-12). And then verse 13 delivers the diagnosis: 'all of this does not satisfy me every time I see Mordecai the Jew sitting at the king's gate.' The word *shavah* ('satisfy') means 'to be worth,' to equal in value. Haman's entire portfolio of honor is worth nothing to him because one man will not add to it. This is pride in its terminal form — not the enjoyment of genuine achievement, but the structural inability to be sufficient without universal deference."
