          "title": "The gallows — pride's logical conclusion",
          "body": "Zeresh and the friends offer the counsel that pride always eventually demands: remove the source of dishonor by force (5:14). The fifty-cubit gallows (roughly 75 feet) is absurdly oversized — no execution requires a structure visible from across the city. But Haman's pride requires a public spectacle that matches the public humiliation he feels. He builds the gallows that same night and plans to request the execution in the morning before going to Esther's banquet. The reader has been tracking two timelines simultaneously since verse 8: Esther's 'tomorrow' for the second banquet, and Haman's 'morning' for Mordecai's execution. They are the same morning. But between Haman's building project and that morning, God will arrange a sleepless king, a book of records, and a public reversal (6:1-11). The gallows Haman builds tonight will hold Haman himself by tomorrow night (7:10). The narrator does not need to announce the irony; he simply records that 'the advice pleased Haman, so he had the gallows made' — and leaves the reader to see what Haman cannot."
