        "body": "The narrator opens the chapter's action with a wardrobe note: Esther *puts on her royal robes* (lavash malkhut, literally 'clothed herself with kingship'). This is not vanity. In the ancient Near East, royal robes carried identity and authority — they signaled to anyone who saw them that the wearer had legitimate standing. Esther dressed for the role she was assigned, not the role she felt. The fasting has ended; the public act begins. The act itself is staggering in its context. According to the law she recited in 4:11, any person who entered the inner court unsummoned was to be put to death 'whether man or woman.' The single exception was the extended scepter — a sovereign act of pardon that the petitioner could not request or predict. Esther takes the risk while the outcome is entirely outside her control.\n\nThe king's response in verse 2 is given with narrative economy that is itself theological. Three clauses: he *saw* her standing, she *found* favor in his sight, he *extended* the scepter. The Hebrew nasa chen ('found favor') is the same idiom that appears at the first critical junctures in Genesis (6:8 of Noah; 39:4 of Joseph) and Exodus (33:12-17 of Moses). It is not earned favor — nasa is the verb 'to find,' not 'to earn.' Something was placed in the king's sight and in his heart that Esther could not manufacture. The Jewish tradition that reads this as the hidden activity of God (Targum Rishon on Esther 5:1-2; b. Megillah 15b) is not eisegesis — it is reading Esther in its canonical grammar. The same construction, the same idiom, the same pattern of human risk met by grace from above appears at every turning point of the rescue narrative.\n\nCalvin, commenting on the Joseph narrative where this idiom also appears, observed: 'The grace of God secretly governs the hearts of men so that they feel an attraction toward those whom God has destined for their benefit — or in whose benefit God's purpose is served.' The principle applies precisely here. Ahasuerus is not presented as a godly man; he is a pagan Persian king who deposed one queen on a drunken whim (1:10-22). That such a man extends the scepter without being asked, without cause visible in the text, is the narrator's theological argument in miniature.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Lavash malkhut* — 'clothed herself with kingship' (5:1); the same verbal root is used in 1 Chronicles 12:18 of the Spirit 'clothing' Amasai. *Nasa chen* — 'to find favor' or 'to lift grace'; the idiom of unmerited reception from a superior, appearing at Genesis 6:8, 39:4, Exodus 33:12. *Sharvit* (scepter, 5:2) appears only in Esther in the Hebrew Bible (also 4:11; 8:4) — a Persian loanword, anchoring the narrative firmly in the historical setting of the Achaemenid court."
