        "body": "The narrative pivot at verse 9 is one of the sharpest tonal reversals in biblical narrative. Haman exits the first banquet in a state of maximum self-satisfaction — 'glad and pleased of heart.' The Hebrew *sameach ve-tov lev* ('joyful and good of heart') is the idiom used in Deuteronomy 28:47 for the joy that Israel was commanded to serve the Lord with, and in Ecclesiastes 9:7 for the simple enjoyment of food and wine. Haman is using the vocabulary of covenant blessing to describe his own self-congratulatory pleasure. Then in a single clause the narrator introduces the reversal: 'but when Haman saw Mordecai in the king's gate and that he did not stand up or tremble before him, Haman was filled with rage against Mordecai.'\n\nThe contrast is total and instantaneous. One man — not defying, not confronting, simply *not standing, not trembling* — is sufficient to evacuate all of Haman's satisfaction. The theological point the narrator is making through narrative rather than direct statement is this: pride built on external honor is structurally insecure. It does not merely need honor; it needs *universal* honor, because a single exception disproves the premise. Haman's rage is not disproportionate to a rational assessment of Mordecai's behavior — it is proportionate to the threat Mordecai poses to the entire architecture of Haman's self-worth.\n\nHaman's self-inventory in verses 11-12 is narrated with clinical precision. Riches (*osher*), sons (*ben*), royal promotion (*gadal nasa*), the queen's exclusive invitation — four categories of social and material capital, catalogued in ascending personal significance. The Talmudic tradition (b. Megillah 15b) counts Haman's sons as ten and reads this as deliberate numerical contrast with the ten sons he will lose in chapter 9. Whether or not that reading is pressed, the inventory itself is the narrator's indictment: a man who must recount his own glory to his household has no genuine possession of it.\n\nVerse 13 is the chapter's theological climax: 'yet all of this does not satisfy me (*eyn shaveh li*) every time I see Mordecai the Jew sitting at the king's gate.' The phrase *eyn shaveh* means 'this is not equal' or 'this does not balance.' Haman's entire portfolio of honor does not weigh enough against the sight of one unmoved Jew. Jonathan Edwards, in *The Nature of True Virtue*, observed that self-love pursued without reference to God produces a soul that can never be full because it is oriented to a finite self rather than an infinite God. Haman is Edwards's portrait in narrative form: a self turned inward on its own honor, unable to receive what it already holds, destroyed by what it cannot control.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chemah* (rage, 5:9) — the same word used of God's burning wrath in Deuteronomy 29:28 and Jeremiah 21:5. Its use for Haman's fury creates an implicit irony: he appropriates the vocabulary of divine indignation for the emotion of wounded vanity. *Kavod* (glory, 5:11) — the word for God's own weightiness and glory (Isaiah 6:3; Exodus 33:18). Haman applies it to his own riches — the most precise single word the narrator could choose to expose the nature of his idolatry."
