        "body": "The chapter's final verse is a counsel scene that functions as a dark mirror of Esther's strategic planning in verses 3-8. Esther carefully arranges circumstances so that the right moment will arrive; Haman's wife and friends arrange for Mordecai's elimination so that Haman will be free to enjoy what is coming. Both involve planning around a royal banquet. The structural parallel is the narrator's irony made architectural.\n\nThe fifty-cubit gallows deserves attention. Fifty cubits is approximately 75 feet — absurdly tall for an execution device and entirely visible above the rooflines of Susa. Several commentators (Jobes, *Esther*, NIV Application Commentary; Bush, *Word Biblical Commentary on Ruth/Esther*) note that the height functions narratively as a symbol of Haman's pride rendered physical: he builds a monument to his own grievance, a structure whose scale exceeds any practical purpose and announces his intention publicly. When the gallows is used in 7:10, the symmetry is complete — the monument becomes the memorial to its builder's fall.\n\nThe counsel of Zeresh and the friends carries a sinister calm. 'Then go joyfully (*sameach*) with the king to the banquet' — the same word *sameach* used of Haman's joy in verse 9, now deployed as the goal of murder. Kill Mordecai in the morning; enjoy the banquet in the afternoon. The logic is the logic of a soul that has made its own comfort the supreme value and will clear any obstacle in its path. The narrator records only that 'the advice pleased Haman, and he had the gallows made' — there is no extended deliberation, no hesitation, no moral weight in the sentence. He simply does it.\n\nThe canonical significance of this verse reaches forward to chapters 6-7. The night Haman builds the gallows is the night the king cannot sleep and calls for the book of records to be read to him (6:1). The morning Haman plans to request Mordecai's execution is the morning he arrives at the palace and is asked by the king, 'What should be done for the man the king wishes to honor?' (6:6). The entire reversal of chapters 6-7 happens in the space that Haman's gallows-building opens. Providence does not prevent the plot; it uses the plot's own timeline as the scaffold on which the reversal is constructed.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ets* (gallows, 5:14) — literally 'tree' or 'wood'; the same word used in Deuteronomy 21:22-23 for the tree on which a hanged criminal was displayed. Paul quotes Deuteronomy 21:23 in Galatians 3:13 for the crucifixion. The wood Haman builds carries a dark resonance in the full canonical frame: the 'tree' of cursed execution is precisely what Haman brings on himself. *Gavoah* (high, 5:14) — the same root as the adjective used for God's exaltation (*gavoah*) in Isaiah 57:15; the exaltation Haman builds for his own purposes will become the site of his humiliation."
